# Task 1 — Build Your First Real Skill: Flashcard Maker

## What This Skill Does

The **Flashcard Maker** skill generates study flashcards in a clean Question–Answer format for any topic the user names — no need to paste notes or source material. This solves a real daily-life problem: as a student, I frequently need to revise topics quickly before exams or quizzes, and manually creating flashcards is time-consuming.

## Why I Chose This Skill / How It Helps My Daily Life

I chose this because flashcard-based revision is something I do regularly while studying, and I was tired of manually formatting Q&A sets every time. This skill lets me simply say a topic name and instantly get a structured, review-ready flashcard set — something I plan to keep using well beyond this assignment.

## How the Skill Works

- **Trigger phrase:** `make flashcards on [topic]`
- **Input:** Just a topic name (the AI generates the content itself using its own knowledge)
- **Output format:** A numbered list of 10 flashcards by default, each with a `Q:` and a short `A:`, ordered from easier to harder concepts
- **Built using:** Anthropic's `skill-creator` skill, through a short clarifying-question interview

## Prompts Used

**Initial prompt (to skill-creator):**
> Build me a flashcard maker skill for studying.

**Clarifying answers given during the skill-creator interview:**
1. Input type: Topic name only (AI generates content itself)
2. Format: Simple Q&A
3. Trigger phrase: "make flashcards"

**Test prompt (in a new chat, without naming the skill):**
> make flashcards on [topic]

## How I Tested It

I opened a new conversation and typed a normal request (`make flashcards on [topic]`) without mentioning the skill by name. The skill triggered automatically and produced the expected format consistently across multiple topics.

## What Worked / What Didn't

- ✅ The skill triggers reliably from natural language without needing the skill name mentioned.
- ✅ Output format stayed consistent across different topics.
- ⚠️ For very broad topics, the skill focuses on the most commonly important facts rather than covering everything — this is expected behavior, not a bug.

## Screenshot(s) to Include

📸 Take a screenshot of a **new chat** where you typed a plain request like `make flashcards on [topic]` **without mentioning the skill name**, showing:
- Your typed prompt
- The skill triggering automatically (the response should show the flashcards in the defined format: `📚 Flashcards: [Topic]` followed by numbered Q&A pairs)

This proves the skill triggers automatically and produces a consistent result.
